# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: las-vegas-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] In computing, an **Atlantic City algorithm** is a randomized algorithm that answers correctly at least 75% of the time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] In some variant definitions, the correctness threshold may be any value greater than 50%.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] In either sense, Atlantic City algorithms are types of Monte Carlo algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] There exists a polynomial-time Atlantic City algorithm for any problem belonging to the class BPP of bounded probabilistic polynomial-time problems.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms, which never return an incorrect answer, are a dual of Monte Carlo algorithms and, therefore, of Atlantic City algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] The name refers to Atlantic City in the U.S. state of New Jersey.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/atlantic-city-algorithm] Much like Monte Carlo and Las Vegas, Atlantic City is widely associated with casinos and gambling culture.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In probability theory, the **expected value** (also called **expectation**, **mean**, or **first moment**) is a generalization of the weighted average.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The expected value of a random variable with a finite number of outcomes is a weighted average of all possible outcomes.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In the case of a continuum of possible outcomes, the expectation is defined by integration.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In the axiomatic foundation for probability provided by measure theory, the expectation is given by Lebesgue integration.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The expected value of a random variable X is often denoted by ${\text{E}}(X)$ , ${\text{E}}[X]$ , or ${\text{E}}X$ , with E also often stylized as $\mathbb {E}$ , ${\mathcal {E}}$ or *E*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The concept of expected value emerged in the mid-17th century from the "problem of points", a puzzle centered on how to *fairly* divide stakes between two players forced to end a game prematurely.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] While the problem had been debated for centuries, it gained new momentum in 1654 when the Chevalier de Méré, a French writer and amateur mathematician, presented it to Blaise Pascal.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Méré claimed that this problem could not be solved and that it showed just how flawed mathematics was when it came to its application to the real world.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Pascal, being a mathematician, decided to work on a solution to the problem.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] He began to discuss the problem in the famous series of letters to Pierre de Fermat.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Soon enough, they both independently came up with a solution.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] They solved the problem in different computational ways, but their results were identical because their computations were based on the same fundamental principle.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The principle is that the value of a future gain should be directly proportional to the chance of getting it.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] This principle seemed to have come naturally to both of them.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] They were very pleased by the fact that they had found essentially the same solution, and this in turn made them absolutely convinced that they had solved the problem conclusively; however, they did not publish their findings.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] They only informed a small circle of mutual scientific friends in Paris about it.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In Dutch mathematician Christiaan Huygens' book, he considered the problem of points, and presented a solution based on the same principle as the solutions of Pascal and Fermat.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Huygens published his treatise in 1657, (see Huygens (1657)) "*De ratiociniis in ludo aleæ*" on probability theory just after visiting Paris.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The book extended the concept of expectation by adding rules for how to calculate expectations in more complicated situations than the original problem (e.g., for three or more players), and can be seen as the first successful attempt at laying down the foundations of the theory of probability.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In the mid-nineteenth century, Pafnuty Chebyshev became the first person to think systematically in terms of the expectations of random variables.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Neither Pascal nor Huygens used the term "expectation" in its modern sense.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The use of the letter E to denote "expected value" goes back to W.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The symbol has since become popular for English writers.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] When "E" is used to denote "expected value", authors use a variety of stylizations: the expectation operator can be stylized as E (upright), E (italic), or $\mathbb {E}$ (in blackboard bold), while a variety of bracket notations (such as E(*X*), E[*X*], and E*X*) are all used.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Another popular notation is μ*X*. ⟨*X*⟩, ⟨*X*⟩av, and ${\overline {X}}$ are commonly used in physics.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] M(*X*) is used in Russian-language literature.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] As discussed above, there are several context-dependent ways of defining the expected value.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The simplest and original definition deals with the case of finitely many possible outcomes, such as in the flip of a coin.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] With the theory of infinite series, this can be extended to the case of countably many possible outcomes.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] It is also very common to consider the distinct case of random variables dictated by (piecewise-)continuous probability density functions, as these arise in many natural contexts.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] All of these specific definitions may be viewed as special cases of the general definition based upon the mathematical tools of measure theory and Lebesgue integration, which provide these different contexts with an axiomatic foundation and common language.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Any definition of expected value may be extended to define an expected value of a multidimensional random variable, i.e. a random vector X .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] It is defined component by component, as $E[X]_{i}=E[X_{i}]$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Similarly, one may define the expected value of a random matrix X with components $X_{ij}$ by $E[X]_{ij}=E[X_{ij}]$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Consider a random variable X with a *finite* list $x_{1},...,x_{k}$ of possible outcomes, each of which (respectively) has probability $p_{1},...,p_{k}$ of occurring.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Since the probabilities must satisfy $p_{1}+...+p_{k}=1$ , it is natural to interpret $E[X]$ as a weighted average of the $x_{i}$ values, with weights given by their probabilities $p_{i}$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In the special case that all possible outcomes are equiprobable (that is $p_{1}=...=p_{k}$ ), the weighted average is given by the standard average.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In the general case, the expected value takes into account the fact that some outcomes are more likely than others.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Informally, the expectation of a random variable with a countably infinite set of possible outcomes is defined analogously as the weighted average of all possible outcomes, where the weights are given by the probabilities of realizing each given value.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] This is to say that $\operatorname {E} [X]=\sum _{i=1}^{\infty }x_{i}\,p_{i},$ where $x_{1},x_{2},...$ are the possible outcomes of the random variable X and $p_{1},p_{2},...$ are their corresponding probabilities.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In many non-mathematical textbooks, this is presented as the full definition of expected values in this context.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] However, there are some subtleties with infinite summation, so the above formula is not suitable as a mathematical definition.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In particular, the Riemann series theorem of mathematical analysis illustrates that the value of certain infinite sums involving positive and negative summands depends on the order in which the summands are given.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Since the outcomes of a random variable have no naturally given order, this creates a difficulty in defining expected value precisely.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] For this reason, many mathematical textbooks only consider the case that the infinite sum given above converges absolutely, which implies that the infinite sum is a finite number independent of the ordering of summands.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Now consider a random variable X which has a probability density function given by a function f on the real number line.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] This means that the probability of X taking on any value in a given open interval is given by the integral of f over that interval.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The density functions of many common distributions are piecewise continuous, and as such the theory is often developed in this restricted setting.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] For such functions, it is sufficient to only consider the standard Riemann integration.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Sometimes *continuous random variables* are defined as those corresponding to this special class of densities, although the term is used differently by various authors.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Analogously to the countably-infinite case above, there are subtleties with this expression due to the infinite region of integration.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Such subtleties can be seen concretely if the distribution of X is given by the Cauchy distribution Cauchy(0, π), so that $f(x)=(x^{2}+\pi ^{2})^{-1}$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] To avoid such ambiguities, in mathematical textbooks it is common to require that the given integral converges absolutely, with $E[X]$ left undefined otherwise.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] However, measure-theoretic notions as given below can be used to give a systematic definition of $E[X]$ for more general random variables X .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] All definitions of the expected value may be expressed in the language of measure theory.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] This is because, in measure theory, the value of the Lebesgue integral of X is defined via weighted averages of *approximations* of X which take on finitely many values.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Moreover, if given a random variable with finitely or countably many possible values, the Lebesgue theory of expectation is identical to the summation formulas given above.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] However, the Lebesgue theory clarifies the scope of the theory of probability density functions.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] These conditions are all equivalent, although this is nontrivial to establish.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In this definition, f is called the *probability density function* of X (relative to Lebesgue measure).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] According to the change-of-variables formula for Lebesgue integration, combined with the law of the unconscious statistician, it follows that $\operatorname {E} [X]\equiv \int _{\Omega }X\,d\operatorname {P} =\int _{\mathbb {R} }xf(x)\,dx$ for any absolutely continuous random variable X .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The above discussion of continuous random variables is thus a special case of the general Lebesgue theory, due to the fact that every piecewise-continuous function is measurable.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The expected value of any real-valued random variable X can also be defined on the graph of its cumulative distribution function F by a nearby equality of areas.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Finally, this is equivalent to the representation $\operatorname {E} [X]=\int _{0}^{\infty }{\bigl (}1-F(x){\bigr )}\,dx-\int _{-\infty }^{0}F(x)\,dx,$ also with convergent integrals.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Expected values as defined above are automatically finite numbers.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] However, in many cases it is fundamental to be able to consider expected values of $\pm \infty$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] This is intuitive, for example, in the case of the St.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Petersburg paradox, in which one considers a random variable with possible outcomes $x_{i}=2^{i}$ , with associated probabilities $p_{i}=2^{-i}$ , for i ranging over all positive integers.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] There is a rigorous mathematical theory underlying such ideas, which is often taken as part of the definition of the Lebesgue integral.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The first fundamental observation is that, whichever of the above definitions are followed, any *nonnegative* random variable whatsoever can be given an unambiguous expected value; whenever absolute convergence fails, then the expected value can be defined as $+\infty$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The second fundamental observation is that any random variable can be written as the difference of two nonnegative random variables.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Given a random variable X , one defines the positive and negative parts by $X^{+}=\max(X,0)$ and $X^{-}=\max(-X,0)$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] These are nonnegative random variables, and it can be directly checked that $X=X^{+}-X^{-}$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] According to this definition, $E[X]$ exists and is finite if and only if $E[X^{+}]$ and $E[X^{-}]$ are both finite.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Due to the formula $\left|X\right|=X^{+}+X^{-}$ , this is the case if and only if $E[\left|X\right|]$ is finite, and this is equivalent to the absolute convergence conditions in the definitions above.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] As such, the present considerations do not define finite expected values in any cases not previously considered; they are only useful for infinite expectations.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] where the integrand is the survival function of X .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The following table gives the expected values of some commonly occurring probability distributions.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The third column gives the expected values both in the form immediately given by the definition, as well as in the simplified form obtained by computation therefrom.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The details of these computations, which are not always straightforward, can be found in the indicated references.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The basic properties below (and their names in bold) replicate or follow immediately from those of Lebesgue integral.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Note that the letters "a.s." stand for "almost surely"—a central property of the Lebesgue integral.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Concentration inequalities control the likelihood of a random variable taking on large values.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] If X is any random variable with finite expectation, then Markov's inequality may be applied to the random variable |*X*−E[*X*]|2 to obtain Chebyshev's inequality $\operatorname {P} (|X-{\text{E}}[X]|\geq a)\leq {\frac {\operatorname {Var} [X]}{a^{2}}},$ where Var is the variance.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] These inequalities are significant for their nearly complete lack of conditional assumptions.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] For example, for any random variable with finite expectation, the Chebyshev inequality implies that there is at least a 75% probability of an outcome being within two standard deviations of the expected value.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] However, in special cases the Markov and Chebyshev inequalities often give much weaker information than is otherwise available.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] For example, in the case of an unweighted dice, Chebyshev's inequality says that odds of rolling between 1 and 6 is at least 53%; in reality, the odds are of course 100%.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The Kolmogorov inequality extends the Chebyshev inequality to the context of sums of random variables.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The following three inequalities are of fundamental importance in the field of mathematical analysis and its applications to probability theory.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The Hölder and Minkowski inequalities can be extended to general measure spaces, and are often given in that context.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] By contrast, the Jensen inequality is special to the case of probability spaces.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In general, it is not the case that $\operatorname {E} [X_{n}]\to \operatorname {E} [X]$ even if $X_{n}\to X$ pointwise.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] Thus, one cannot interchange limits and expectation, without additional conditions on the random variables.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] An example is easily obtained by setting $Y_{0}=X_{1}$ and $Y_{n}=X_{n+1}-X_{n}$ for $n\geq 1,$ where $X_{n}$ is as in the previous example.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] A number of convergence results specify exact conditions which allow one to interchange limits and expectations, as specified below.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The expectation of a random variable plays an important role in a variety of contexts.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In statistics, where one seeks estimates for unknown parameters based on available data gained from samples, the sample mean serves as an estimate for the expectation, and is itself a random variable.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In such settings, the sample mean is considered to meet the desirable criterion for a "good" estimator in being unbiased; that is, the expected value of the estimate is equal to the true value of the underlying parameter.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] For a different example, in decision theory, an agent making an optimal choice in the context of incomplete information is often assumed to maximize the expected value of their utility function.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] It is possible to construct an expected value equal to the probability of an event by taking the expectation of an indicator function that is one if the event has occurred and zero otherwise.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] This relationship can be used to translate properties of expected values into properties of probabilities, e.g. using the law of large numbers to justify estimating probabilities by frequencies.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The expected values of the powers of *X* are called the moments of *X*; the moments about the mean of *X* are expected values of powers of *X* − E[*X*].
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The moments of some random variables can be used to specify their distributions, via their moment generating functions.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] To empirically estimate the expected value of a random variable, one repeatedly measures observations of the variable and computes the arithmetic mean of the results.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] If the expected value exists, this procedure estimates the true expected value in an unbiased manner and has the property of minimizing the sum of the squares of the residuals (the sum of the squared differences between the observations and the estimate).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The law of large numbers demonstrates (under fairly mild conditions) that, as the size of the sample gets larger, the variance of this estimate gets smaller.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] In classical mechanics, the center of mass is an analogous concept to expectation.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] For example, suppose *X* is a discrete random variable with values *xi* and corresponding probabilities *pi.* Now consider a weightless rod on which are placed weights, at locations *xi* along the rod and having masses *pi* (whose sum is one).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] The point at which the rod balances is E[*X*].
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/expected-value] A very important application of the expectation value is in the field of quantum mechanics.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] In computing, a **Las Vegas algorithm** is a randomized algorithm that always gives correct results; that is, it always produces the correct result or it informs about the failure.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, the runtime of a Las Vegas algorithm differs depending on the input.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The usual definition of a Las Vegas algorithm includes the restriction that the *expected* runtime be finite, where the expectation is carried out over the space of random information, or entropy, used in the algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] An alternative definition requires that a Las Vegas algorithm always terminates (is effective), but may output a symbol not part of the solution space to indicate failure in finding a solution.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The nature of Las Vegas algorithms makes them suitable in situations where the number of possible solutions is limited, and where verifying the correctness of a candidate solution is relatively easy while finding a solution is complex.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Systematic search methods for computationally hard problems, such as some variants of the Davis–Putnam algorithm for propositional satisfiability (SAT), also utilize non-deterministic decisions, and can thus also be considered Las Vegas algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms were introduced by László Babai in 1979, in the context of the graph isomorphism problem, as a dual to Monte Carlo algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Babai introduced the term "Las Vegas algorithm" alongside an example involving coin flips: the algorithm depends on a series of independent coin flips, and there is a small chance of failure (no result).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, in contrast to Monte Carlo algorithms, the Las Vegas algorithm can guarantee the correctness of any reported result.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] As mentioned above, Las Vegas algorithms always return correct results.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The code above illustrates this property.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The goal is to find an index in the array `a` that contains the value 1.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] A variable `k` is generated randomly; after `k` is generated, `k` is used to index the array `a`.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] If this index contains the value 1, then `k` is returned; otherwise, the algorithm repeats this process until it finds 1.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Although this Las Vegas algorithm is guaranteed to find the correct answer, it does not have a fixed runtime; due to the randomization, it is possible for arbitrarily much time to elapse before the algorithm terminates.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] This section provides the conditions that characterize an algorithm's being of Las Vegas type.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] some tmax such that P(RTA,x ≤ tmax) = 1.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Approximate completeness is primarily of theoretical interest, as the time limits for finding solutions are usually too large to be of practical use.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms have different criteria for the evaluation based on the problem setting.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] These criteria are divided into three categories with different time limits since Las Vegas algorithms do not have set time complexity.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] For Type 1 where there is no time limit, the average run-time can represent the run-time behavior.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Here, *P*(*RT* ≤ *tmax*), which is the probability of finding a solution within time, describes its run-time behavior.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] In case of Type 3, its run-time behavior can only be represented by the run-time distribution function *rtd*: *R* → [0,1] defined as *rtd*(*t*) = *P*(*RT* ≤ *t*) or its approximation.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The run-time distribution (RTD) is the distinctive way to describe the run-time behavior of a Las Vegas algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] With this data, we can easily get other criteria such as the mean run-time, standard deviation, median, percentiles, or success probabilities *P*(*RT* ≤ *t*) for arbitrary time-limits *t*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms arise frequently in search problems.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] For example, one looking for some information online might search related websites for the desired information.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The time complexity thus ranges from getting "lucky" and finding the content immediately, to being "unlucky" and spending large amounts of time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Once the right website is found, then there is no possibility of error.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] A simple example is randomized quicksort, where the pivot is chosen randomly, and divides the elements into three partitions: elements less than pivot, elements equal to pivot, and elements greater than pivot.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] QuickSort always generates the solution, which in this case the sorted array.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Unfortunately, the time complexity is not that obvious.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] It turns out that the runtime depends on which element we pick as a pivot.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The runtime of quicksort depends heavily on how well the pivot is selected.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] If a value of pivot is either too big or small, the partition will be unbalanced, resulting in a poor runtime efficiency.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, if the value of pivot is near the middle of the array, then the split will be reasonably well balanced, yielding a faster runtime.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Since the pivot is randomly picked, the running time will be good most of the time and bad occasionally.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] In the case of average case, it is hard to determine since the analysis does not depend on the input distribution but on the random choices that the algorithm makes.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The average of quicksort is computed over all possible random choices that the algorithm might make when choosing the pivot.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Although the worst-case runtime is Θ(*n*2), the average-case runtime is Θ(*n*log*n*).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] It turns out that the worst-case does not happen often.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] For large values of *n*, the runtime is Θ(*n*log*n*) with a high probability.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Note that the probability that the pivot is the middle value element each time is one out of *n* numbers, which is very rare.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, it is still the same runtime when the split is 10%-90% instead of a 50%–50% because the depth of the recursion tree will still be *O*(log*n*) with *O*(*n*) times taken each level of recursion.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The eight queens problem is usually solved with a backtracking algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, a Las Vegas algorithm can be applied; in fact, it is more efficient than backtracking.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Place 8 queens on a chessboard so that no one attacks another.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Remember that a queen attacks other pieces on the same row, column and diagonals.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Assume that *k* rows, 0 ≤ *k* ≤ 8, are successfully occupied by queens.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Otherwise, proceed to occupy row *k* + 1.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Calculate all positions on this row not attacked by existing queens.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Otherwise, pick one at random, increment *k* and repeat.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Note that the algorithm simply fails if a queen cannot be placed.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] But the process can be repeated and every time will generate different arrangement.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The complexity class of decision problems that have Las Vegas algorithms with expected polynomial runtime is ZPP.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] which is intimately connected with the way Las Vegas algorithms are sometimes constructed.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Namely the class RP consists of all decision problems for which a randomized polynomial-time algorithm exists that always answers correctly when the correct answer is "no", but is allowed to be wrong with a certain probability bounded away from one when the answer is "yes".
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] When such an algorithm exists for both a problem and its complement (with the answers "yes" and "no" swapped), the two algorithms can be run simultaneously and repeatedly: run each for a constant number of steps, taking turns, until one of them returns a definitive answer.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] This is the standard way to construct a Las Vegas algorithm that runs in expected polynomial time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Note that in general there is no worst case upper bound on the run time of a Las Vegas algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] In order to make a Las Vegas algorithm optimal, the expected run time should be minimized.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Designing a strategy that is optimal among all strategies for *A*(*x*), given the full information about the distribution of *TA*(*x*).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The existence of the optimal strategy might be a fascinating theoretical observation.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, it is not practical in real life because it is not easy to find the information of distribution of *TA*(*x*).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Furthermore, there is no point of running the experiment repeatedly to obtain the information about the distribution since most of the time, the answer is needed only once for any *x*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms can be contrasted with Monte Carlo algorithms, in which the resources used are bounded but the answer may be incorrect with a certain (typically small) probability.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] A Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm by running it for set time and generating a random answer when it fails to terminate.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] By an application of Markov's inequality, we can set the bound on the probability that the Las Vegas algorithm would go over the fixed limit.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] If a deterministic way to test for correctness is available, then it is possible to turn a Monte Carlo algorithm into a Las Vegas algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] However, it is hard to convert a Monte Carlo algorithm to a Las Vegas algorithm without a way to test the algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] On the other hand, changing a Las Vegas algorithm to a Monte Carlo algorithm is easy.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] This can be done by running a Las Vegas algorithm for a specific period of time given by confidence parameter.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] If the algorithm finds the solution within the time, then it is success and if not then output can simply be "sorry".
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Assume that there is an array with the length of even *n*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Half of the entries in the array are 0's and the remaining half are 1's.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] The goal here is to find an index that contains a 1.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Since Las Vegas does not end until it finds 1 in the array, it does not gamble with the correctness but run-time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] On the other hand, Monte Carlo runs 300 times, which means it is impossible to know that Monte Carlo will find "1" in the array within 300 times of loops until it actually executes the code.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/las-vegas-algorithm] Therefore, unlike Las Vegas, Monte Carlo does not gamble with run-time but correctness.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] In computing, a **Monte Carlo algorithm** is a randomized algorithm whose output may be incorrect with a certain (typically small) probability.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Two examples of such algorithms are the Karger–Stein algorithm and the Monte Carlo algorithm for minimum feedback arc set.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] The name refers to the Monte Carlo casino in the Principality of Monaco, which is well-known around the world as an icon of gambling.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] The term "Monte Carlo" was first introduced in 1947 by Nicholas Metropolis.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Las Vegas algorithms are a dual of Monte Carlo algorithms and never return an incorrect answer.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] However, they may make random choices as part of their work.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] As a result, the time taken might vary between runs, even with the same input.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] If there is a procedure for verifying whether the answer given by a Monte Carlo algorithm is correct, and the probability of a correct answer is bounded above zero, then with probability one, running the algorithm repeatedly while testing the answers will eventually give a correct answer.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Whether this process is a Las Vegas algorithm depends on whether halting with probability one is considered to satisfy the definition.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] While the answer returned by a deterministic algorithm is always expected to be correct, this is not the case for Monte Carlo algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] For decision problems, these algorithms are generally classified as either **false**-biased or **true**-biased.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] A **false**-biased Monte Carlo algorithm is always correct when it returns **false**; a **true**-biased algorithm is always correct when it returns **true**.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] While this describes algorithms with *one-sided errors*, others might have no bias; these are said to have *two-sided errors*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] The answer they provide (either **true** or **false**) will be incorrect, or correct, with some bounded probability.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] For instance, the Solovay–Strassen primality test is used to determine whether a given number is a prime number.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] It always answers **true** for prime number inputs; for composite inputs, it answers **false** with probability at least 1⁄2 and **true** with probability less than 1⁄2.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Thus, **false** answers from the algorithm are certain to be correct, whereas the **true** answers remain uncertain; this is said to be a *1⁄2-correct false-biased algorithm*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] For a Monte Carlo algorithm with one-sided errors, the failure probability can be reduced (and the success probability amplified) by running the algorithm *k* times.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Consider again the Solovay–Strassen algorithm which is *1⁄2-correct false-biased*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] One may run this algorithm multiple times returning a **false** answer if it reaches a **false** response within *k* iterations, and otherwise returning **true**.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Thus, if the number is prime then the answer is always correct, and if the number is composite then the answer is correct with probability at least 1−(1−1⁄2)*k* = 1−2*−k*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] For Monte Carlo decision algorithms with two-sided error, the failure probability may again be reduced by running the algorithm *k* times and returning the majority function of the answers.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] In contrast, the complexity class ZPP describes problems solvable by polynomial expected time Las Vegas algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] ZPP ⊆ RP ⊆ BPP, but it is not known whether any of these complexity classes is distinct from each other; that is, Monte Carlo algorithms may have more computational power than Las Vegas algorithms, but this has not been proven.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Another complexity class, PP, describes decision problems with a polynomial-time Monte Carlo algorithm that is more accurate than flipping a coin but where the error probability cannot necessarily be bounded away from 1⁄2.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are primarily divided by its two main types, Monte Carlo and Las Vegas, however, these represent only a top of the hierarchy and can be further categorized.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Previous table represents a general framework for Monte Carlo and Las Vegas randomized algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Instead of the mathematical symbol < one could use $\leq$ , thus making probabilities in the worst case equal.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/monte-carlo-algorithm] Well-known Monte Carlo algorithms include the Solovay–Strassen primality test, the Baillie–PSW primality test, the Miller–Rabin primality test, and certain fast variants of the Schreier–Sims algorithm in computational group theory.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] In computer science, **quickselect** is a selection algorithm to find the *k*th smallest element in an unordered list, also known as the *k*th order statistic.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Like the related quicksort sorting algorithm, it was developed by Tony Hoare, and thus is also known as **Hoare's selection algorithm**.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Like quicksort, it is efficient in practice and has good average-case performance, but has poor worst-case performance.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Quickselect and its variants are the selection algorithms most often used in efficient real-world implementations.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Quickselect uses the same overall approach as quicksort, choosing one element as a pivot and partitioning the data in two based on the pivot, accordingly as less than or greater than the pivot.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] However, instead of recursing into both sides, as in quicksort, quickselect only recurses into one side – the side with the element it is searching for.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] This reduces the average complexity from $O(n\log n)$ to $O(n)$ , with a worst case of $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] As with quicksort, quickselect is generally implemented as an in-place algorithm, and beyond selecting the kth element, it also partially sorts the data.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] See selection algorithm for further discussion of the connection with sorting.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] In quicksort, there is a subprocedure called `partition` that can, in linear time, group a list (ranging from indices `left` to `right`) into two parts: those less than a certain element, and those greater than or equal to the element.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] This is known as the Lomuto partition scheme, which is simpler but less efficient than Hoare's original partition scheme.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] In quicksort, we recursively sort both branches, leading to best-case $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] However, when doing selection, we already know which partition our desired element lies in, since the pivot is in its final sorted position, with all those preceding it in an unsorted order and all those following it in an unsorted order.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Just as the minimum-based selection algorithm is a partial selection sort, this is a partial quicksort, generating and partitioning only $O(\log n)$ of its $O(n)$ partitions.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] This simple procedure has expected linear performance, and, like quicksort, has quite good performance in practice.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] This `select` function works only with the Lomuto partition scheme.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] This is because `select` assumes that the return value from partition is the position of the pivot.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] This is true for the Lomuto partition scheme, but not for the Hoare's partition scheme.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] In Hoare's scheme, the return value is the last index of the "left" partition, and the pivot is not guaranteed to be "in between" the partitions.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] The recursion, as presented, also only works with Lomuto's scheme, as it assumes that the right partition starts with `pivotIndex +1`, while when using Hoare's scheme, the right partition starts at `pivotIndex`.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Like quicksort, quickselect has good average performance, but is sensitive to the pivot that is chosen.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] However, if bad pivots are consistently chosen, such as decreasing by only a single element each time, then worst-case performance is quadratic: $O(n^{2}).$ This occurs, for example, in searching for the maximum element of a set, using the first element as the pivot, and having sorted data.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] However, for randomly chosen pivots, this worst case is very unlikely: the probability of using more than $Cn$ comparisons, for any sufficiently large constant C , is superexponentially small as a function of C .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] The easiest solution is to choose a random pivot, which yields almost certain linear time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Deterministically, one can use the median-of-3 pivot strategy (as in Quicksort), which yields linear performance on partially sorted data, as is common in the real world.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] However, contrived sequences can still cause worst-case complexity; David Musser describes a "median-of-3 killer" sequence that allows an attack against that strategy, which was one motivation for his introselect algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] One can assure linear performance even in the worst case by using a more sophisticated pivot strategy; this is done in the median of medians algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] However, the overhead of computing the pivot is high, and thus, this is generally not used in practice.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] One can combine basic quickselect with median of medians as a fallback to get both fast average case performance and linear worst-case performance; this is done in introselect.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] Finer computations of the average time complexity yield a worst case of $n(2+2\log 2+o(1))\leq 3.4n+o(n)$ for random pivots (in the case of the median; other *k* are faster).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/quickselect] The constant can be improved to 3/2 by a more complicated pivot strategy, yielding the Floyd–Rivest algorithm, which has average complexity of $1.5n+O(n^{1/2})$ for median, with other *k* being faster.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] A **randomized algorithm** is an algorithm that employs a degree of randomness as part of its logic or procedure.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In some cases, probabilistic algorithms are the only practical means of solving a problem.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] As a motivating example, consider the problem of finding an ‘*a*’ in an array of *n* elements.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] We give two versions of the algorithm, one Las Vegas algorithm and one Monte Carlo algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm succeeds with probability 1.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Since it is constant, the expected run time over many calls is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] If an ‘*a*’ is found, the algorithm succeeds, else the algorithm fails.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] This algorithm does not guarantee success, but the run time is bounded.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The number of iterations is always less than or equal to k.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Taking k to be constant the run time (expected and absolute) is $\Theta (1)$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Randomized algorithms are particularly useful when faced with a malicious "adversary" or attacker who deliberately tries to feed a bad input to the algorithm (see worst-case complexity and competitive analysis (online algorithm)) such as in the Prisoner's dilemma.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] It is for this reason that randomness is ubiquitous in cryptography.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In cryptographic applications, pseudo-random numbers cannot be used, since the adversary can predict them, making the algorithm effectively deterministic.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, either a source of truly random numbers or a cryptographically secure pseudo-random number generator is required.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Another area in which randomness is inherent is quantum computing.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In the example above, the Las Vegas algorithm always outputs the correct answer, but its running time is a random variable.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The Monte Carlo algorithm (related to the Monte Carlo method for simulation) is guaranteed to complete in an amount of time that can be bounded by a function the input size and its parameter *k*, but allows a *small probability of error*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Observe that any Las Vegas algorithm can be converted into a Monte Carlo algorithm (via Markov's inequality), by having it output an arbitrary, possibly incorrect answer if it fails to complete within a specified time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Conversely, if an efficient verification procedure exists to check whether an answer is correct, then a Monte Carlo algorithm can be converted into a Las Vegas algorithm by running the Monte Carlo algorithm repeatedly till a correct answer is obtained.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Computational complexity theory models randomized algorithms as *probabilistic Turing machines*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Both Las Vegas and Monte Carlo algorithms are considered, and several complexity classes are studied.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Problem classes having (possibly nonterminating) algorithms with polynomial time average case running time whose output is always correct are said to be in ZPP.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The class of problems for which both YES and NO-instances are allowed to be identified with some error is called BPP.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] This class acts as the randomized equivalent of P, i.e.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] BPP represents the class of efficient randomized algorithms.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort was discovered by Tony Hoare in 1959, and subsequently published in 1961.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, Hoare published the quickselect algorithm, which finds the median element of a list in linear expected time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] It remained open until 1973 whether a deterministic linear-time algorithm existed.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In 1917, Henry Cabourn Pocklington introduced a randomized algorithm known as Pocklington's algorithm for efficiently finding square roots modulo prime numbers.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Elwyn Berlekamp introduced a randomized algorithm for efficiently computing the roots of a polynomial over a finite field.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Solovay and Volker Strassen discovered a polynomial-time randomized primality test (i.e., determining the primality of a number).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Rabin demonstrated that the 1976 Miller's primality test could also be turned into a polynomial-time randomized algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] At that time, no provably polynomial-time deterministic algorithms for primality testing were known.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] One of the earliest randomized data structures is the hash table, which was introduced in 1953 by Hans Peter Luhn at IBM.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Luhn's hash table used chaining to resolve collisions and was also one of the first applications of linked lists.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Subsequently, in 1954, Gene Amdahl, Elaine M.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] McGraw, Nathaniel Rochester, and Arthur Samuel of IBM Research introduced linear probing, although Andrey Ershov independently had the same idea in 1957.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In 1962, Donald Knuth performed the first correct analysis of linear probing, although the memorandum containing his analysis was not published until much later.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The first published analysis was due to Konheim and Weiss in 1966.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Early works on hash tables either assumed access to a fully random hash function or assumed that the keys themselves were random.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In 1979, Carter and Wegman introduced universal hash functions, which they showed could be used to implement chained hash tables with constant expected time per operation.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Early work on randomized data structures also extended beyond hash tables.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In 1970, Burton Howard Bloom introduced an approximate-membership data structure known as the Bloom filter.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Aragon introduced a randomized balanced search tree known as the treap.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In the same year, William Pugh introduced another randomized search tree known as the skip list.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Prior to the popularization of randomized algorithms in computer science, Paul Erdős popularized the use of randomized constructions as a mathematical technique for establishing the existence of mathematical objects.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] This technique has become known as the probabilistic method.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Erdős gave his first application of the probabilistic method in 1947, when he used a simple randomized construction to establish the existence of Ramsey graphs.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] He famously used a more sophisticated randomized algorithm in 1959 to establish the existence of graphs with high girth and chromatic number.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Quicksort is a familiar, commonly used algorithm in which randomness can be useful.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Many deterministic versions of this algorithm require *O*(*n*2) time to sort *n* numbers for some well-defined class of degenerate inputs (such as an already sorted array), with the specific class of inputs that generate this behavior defined by the protocol for pivot selection.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] However, if the algorithm selects pivot elements uniformly at random, it has a provably high probability of finishing in *O*(*n* log *n*) time regardless of the characteristics of the input.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In computational geometry, a standard technique to build a structure like a convex hull or Delaunay triangulation is to randomly permute the input points and then insert them one by one into the existing structure.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The randomization ensures that the expected number of changes to the structure caused by an insertion is small, and so the expected running time of the algorithm can be bounded from above.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] This technique is known as randomized incremental construction.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Recall that the contraction of two nodes, *u* and *v*, in a (multi-)graph yields a new node *u* ' with edges that are the union of the edges incident on either *u* or *v*, except from any edge(s) connecting *u* and *v*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Figure 1 gives an example of contraction of vertex *A* and *B*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] After contraction, the resulting graph may have parallel edges, but contains no self loops.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] In each execution of the outer loop, the algorithm repeats the inner loop until only 2 nodes remain, the corresponding cut is obtained.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The run time of one execution is $O(n)$ , and *n* denotes the number of vertices.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] After *m* times executions of the outer loop, we output the minimum cut among all the results.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The figure 2 gives an example of one execution of the algorithm.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] After execution, we get a cut of size 3.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] If *G* is not connected, then *G* can be partitioned into *L* and *R* without any edge between them.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] So the min cut in a disconnected graph is 0.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Initially, *u*,*v* are distinct vertices.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] *As long as we pick an edge ⁠ $f\neq e$ ⁠, u and v do not get merged.* Thus, at the end of the algorithm, we have two compound nodes covering the entire graph, one consisting of the vertices of *L* and the other consisting of the vertices of *R*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] As in figure 2, the size of min cut is 1, and *C* = {(*A*,*B*)}.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] If we don't select (*A*,*B*) for contraction, we can get the min cut.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Because the min cut is *k*, every vertex *v* must satisfy degree(*v*) ≥ *k*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Therefore, the sum of the degree is at least *pk*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] But it is well known that the sum of vertex degrees equals 2|*E*|.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the algorithm succeeds is 1 − the probability that all attempts fail.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] By lemma 1, the probability that *C**i* = *C* is the probability that no edge of *C* is selected during iteration *i*.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Consider the inner loop and let *G**j* denote the graph after *j* edge contractions, where *j* ∈ {0, 1, …, *n* − 3}.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] We use the chain rule of conditional possibilities.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The probability that the edge chosen at iteration *j* is not in *C*, given that no edge of *C* has been chosen before, is $1-{\frac {k}{|E(G_{j})|}}$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Note that *G**j* still has min cut of size *k*, so by Lemma 2, it still has at least ${\frac {(n-j)k}{2}}$ edges.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Thus the probability that the algorithm succeeds is at least $1-\left(1-{\frac {2}{n(n-1)}}\right)^{m}$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] The algorithm finds the min cut with probability $1-{\frac {1}{n}}$ , in time $O(mn)=O(n^{3}\log n)$ .
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Randomness can be viewed as a resource, like space and time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] Derandomization is then the process of *removing* randomness (or using as little of it as possible).
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] It is not currently known if all algorithms can be derandomized without significantly increasing their running time.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] For instance, in computational complexity, it is unknown whether P = BPP, i.e., we do not know whether we can take an arbitrary randomized algorithm that runs in polynomial time with a small error probability and derandomize it to run in polynomial time without using randomness.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] When the model of computation is restricted to Turing machines, it is currently an open question whether the ability to make random choices allows some problems to be solved in polynomial time that cannot be solved in polynomial time without this ability; this is the question of whether P = BPP.
[src:las-vegas-algorithms/randomized-algorithm] However, in other contexts, there are specific examples of problems where randomization yields strict improvements.
